        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> If you `nvim_set_current_buf` to the scratch buffer, that doesn't seem too surprising.\r\n\r\nThe command is for the buffer in the other (not the one being closed) tabpage.\r\n\r\nThe behavior is surprising because the presence of the never shown buffer dictates the behavior. With this 'init.lua' everything works as expected, although the `[No name]` buffer is not shown before or after deleting a scratch buffer:\r\n\r\n```lua\r\nvim.api.nvim_set_current_buf(vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, true))\r\n\r\n-- Make a tabpage with another scratch buffer\r\n_G.new_scratch_tabpage = function()\r\n  vim.cmd.sbuffer({ vim.api.nvim_create_buf(false, true), mods = { tab = vim.fn.tabpagenr() } })\r\nend\r\n```\r\n\r\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/57d13181-4a50-4064-ac46-a1f4ebf5dcbc\r\n\r\nIf this is an intended behavior (which I presume needs to be decided inside issue in vim/vim, right?), then I guess an explicit closing of the confirmation window/tabpage is needed after all. This situation (two scratch buffers) will be more or less common in the wild when doing `vim.pack.update()` from inside dashboard type of buffer just after starting Nvim.",
